                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <date from="1101" to="1200">12th century</date>. Unknown origin, but France has been propoesd by the editor of the <quote>Liber officialis</quote> of Amalarius of Metz, see <bibl>
                                    <title ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107563">Hanssens </title>
                                    <citedRange from="434" to="434" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The manuscript's early provenance is unknown.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>In the early 17th century, the volume belonged to the library of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102748">Peter Vok Ursinus of Rosenberg</persName> as attested to by the ex libris on the <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>. The library was at that time housed at his castle in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100349">Třeboň</placeName> (Wittingau), but was later confiscated and in 1647 relocated to the castle in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100067">Prague</placeName> by orders of the emperor Ferdinand III.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>The volume was probably taken as spoils of war in the battle of <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100067">Prague</placeName> in 1648, when the castle and its library was looted. It was thereafter brought to <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100081">Sweden</placeName> and incorporated into the <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100040">Royal Library</placeName>. It is probably the volume listed as <quote>Isidori Episcopi Homiliae in Ezechielem. Eiusdem Sententiae. Amalarius De Rebus et Ordine Romanae Ecclesiae. Membrana</quote> on p. 49 in Vossius's catalogue from 1651, see <bibl>
                                    <title ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107511">Callmer</title>
                                </bibl>. There are two signa on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>. Signum <quote>36</quote> is used for this volume in the catalogue from 1734 (U 125e), f. 17, signum <quote>e.30.4.11</quote> is from Hammarsköld’s catalogue from the nineteenth century (U 133).</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
