                                <textLang mainLang="la"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102527"> Gregory I </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">Homilies on Ezekiel, Book 2</title>
                                <rubric>Incipit Omelia TERCIA DECIMA</rubric>
                                <incipit>QUONIAM MVLTIS CVRIS PREMentibus in hiezechiel propheta librum coram uestra caritate</incipit>
                                <explicit>Sit itaque gloria omnipotenti domino nostro ihesu christo qui uiuit et regnat cum patre in unitate spiritus sancti deus per omnia secula seculorum AMEN.</explicit>
                                <finalRubric>Explicit exposicio libri iezechielis prophete</finalRubric>
                                <note>
                                    <p> The final rubric on <locus from="68r" to="68r" scheme="folios"/> is erroneously written below the rubric for the subsequent section but letters <quote>a</quote> and <quote>b</quote> have been added to indicate the correct order.</p>
                                    <p/>
                                </note>
                                <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107522">Adriaen (1971)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="205" to="398" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="68v" to="130v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <textLang mainLang="la"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102749"> Isidore of Seville </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">Sentences</title>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="68r" to="69v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <author>
                                        <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102749"> Isidore of Seville </persName>
                                    </author>
                                    <title type="desc">Letter to Bishop Masona</title>
                                    <rubric>Domino sancto meritisque beato Masone episcopo ysidorus episcopus</rubric>
                                    <incipit>UENIENTE AD NOS famulo uestro uiro religioso <sic>nicentio</sic> litteras honorificentie uestre nobis detulit</incipit>
                                    <explicit>Datum sub die pridie KL martias anno tercio regni domini nostri gloriosissimi <sic>Wittirici</sic> regis </explicit>
                                    <note>
                                        <p>A first rubric to this letter is on <locus from="68r" to="68r" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                                        <p>The letter is followed by two shorter texts. The first is the text of Canon 20 from the Synod of Ancyra: <quote>Hera. Canon anquiritani. Si quis uel si qua adulterium commiserit vii annis oportet perfectionem consequi secundum pristinos gradus</quote> (edited in <bibl>
                                                <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107550">Turner (1899)</title>
                                                <citedRange from="106" to="106" unit="page"/>
                                            </bibl>). This is characteristic for the letter's transmission in the <quote>Collectio Vetus Gallica</quote>, see <bibl>
                                                <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107549">Mordek (1975)</title>
                                                <citedRange from="227" to="228" unit="page"/>
                                            </bibl>.</p>
                                        <p>The second text is an unidentified poem beginning <quote>Accipe Laurenti per que istud nostri pignus amoris habe</quote>, and ending <quote>quem quicumque sapit mox et amare potest</quote>. The same text is found in the manuscript <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100359">Göttweig</placeName>, Benediktinerstift, cod. 174, which transmits Isidore's <quote xml:lang="en">Sentences</quote> together with the letter to Massona, Canon 20 and the account of the vision, see below 2.3. The poem is not listed in the online catalogue available at <ref target="https://manuscripta.at/?ID=36648">manuscripta.at</ref> but the incipit is quoted in the earlier, handwritten catalogue by Vinzenz Werl from 1843, also available at <ref target="https://manuscripta.at/?ID=36648">manuscripta.at</ref>, <quote>Literatur zur Handschrift</quote>.</p>
                                    </note>
                                    <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107525">PL 83</title>
                                        <citedRange from="899A" to="902A" unit="column"/>
                                    </bibl>
                                </msItem>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="69v" to="129v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <author>
                                        <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102749"> Isidore of Seville </persName>
                                    </author>
                                    <title type="desc">Sentences</title>
                                    <rubric>Incipit liber primus sententiarum sancti <sic>ysynori</sic>
                                    </rubric>
                                    <incipit>QVOD DEVS SVMMVS ET INCOMVTABILIS Sit Summum bonum deus est</incipit>
                                    <explicit>non quos celestis aula letificandos includit</explicit>
                                    <note>Book 1: <locus from="69v" to="84r" scheme="folios"/>; Book 2: <locus from="84r" to="103r" scheme="folios"/>; Book 3: <locus from="103r" to="129v" scheme="folios"/>. Each book is preceded by a list of numbered chapter headings, some of which do not correspond to the numbering in the edition.</note>
                                    <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107524">Cazier (1998)</title>
                                    </bibl>
                                </msItem>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="129v" to="130v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">A vision</title>
                                    <incipit>FVIT QVIDAM Frater Qui eductus e corpore multas mirabiles uidit in spiritu uisiones </incipit>
                                    <explicit>corpus suum inter cottidiana ieiunia domabat multisque et uerbo et conuersacione exemplum <sic>sint</sic> ad salutem perpetuam Adiuuante domino nostro ihesu christo qui uiuit et regnat in secula seculorum AMEN</explicit>
                                    <note>This text, sometimes referred to as <quote>Visio Isidori</quote>, is a rewritten account of the <quote>Vision of the Monk of Wenlock</quote>, described by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102759">Boniface</persName> in Epistula 10, to Abbess Eadburga of Minster-in-Thanet. The vision is transmitted with the Sentences also in the manuscript <ref target="https://manuscripta.at/?ID=36648">Göttweig, Benediktinerstift, cod. 174</ref>, see also above 2.1.</note>
                                </msItem>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="131r" to="159v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102760"> Amalarius of Metz </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">De ecclesiasticis officiis</title>
                                <rubric>INCIPIT Liber AMALARII VIRI DOCTISSIMI DE REBVS ET DE ORDINE ROMANE AECCLESIAE</rubric>
                                <incipit>POSTQVAM Scripsi libellum qui mea paruitate uocatur de ecclesiastico officio</incipit>
                                <explicit>quem morem in suis prepositis eciam nunc seruat aecclesia.</explicit>
                                <note>This is the version of the <quote>Liber officialis</quote> called <quote>Retractatio prima</quote> by the editor, J.M. Hanssens, with a further revision, see <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107563">Hanssens (1935)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="434" to="435" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl>, and <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107562">Hanssens (1948)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="129" to="129" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl>.</note>
                                <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107562">Hanssens (1948)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="2" to="2" unit="volume"/>
                                    <citedRange from="13" to="543" unit="page"/>
                                    <note>The prologue, <quote>Postquam scripsi</quote>, and parts of the text are the same as in the edition. Not all chapters in the edition are in the manuscript and the manuscript has chapters that are not in the edition</note>
                                </bibl>
                            </msItem>
                        </msContents>
